6. Background & Literature Review
Small retail and service businesses often rely on digital order-booking systems to manage sales, stock, and customer communication. Studying similar systems helps identify what works well and what problems still exist, so the new design can improve on them
Small retail and service businesses often rely on digital order-booking systems to manage sales, stock, and customer communication. Studying similar systems helps identify what works well and what problems still exist, so the new design can improve on them.
6.1 Existing Order and Booking Systems
Several common solutions are used by small businesses today:
●	E-commerce platforms such as Shopify and WooCommerce allow product listings, online ordering, and payment handling through a web interface.
●	Marketplace apps like Etsy or Instagram Shops let sellers reach large audiences but give limited control over features and data.
●	Custom web systems built with tools like PHP + MSSQL or WordPress plugins are flexible but often require technical knowledge to set up and maintain.
6.2 Strengths of Existing Approaches
●	Automation: These platforms reduce manual work by generating order records and confirmations automatically.
●	Accessibility: They run in a browser or mobile app, so customers can order anytime.
●	Integration: Many include built-in payment and delivery options, giving a full shopping experience.
●	User Interface: Most have simple, guided order flows that are easy for customers to understand.

6.3 Weaknesses and Gaps
●	Limited Customisation: Ready-made platforms rarely match a small business’s exact workflow, such as communicating with a specific wholesaler.
●	High Cost or Fees: Subscription charges or sales commissions reduce profit for small sellers.
●	Data Ownership: Some third-party platforms store data on external servers, meaning the business has less control over customer information.
●	Complex Setup: Building or hosting a custom site can be difficult without technical help.
●	Over-sized Features: Many commercial systems include advanced marketing or analytics tools that small businesses do not need at the start, making them harder to use.

6.4 Technology Choices and Tools Used (Python, JavaScript, MSSQL): 
6.4.1 Python (Backend Development) 
Python was picked for the backend because it has clear, easy-to-read syntax and lots of libraries that speed up development.Python also works well with relational databases through ORMs, so data such as orders and customer details can be handled safely and efficiently. For this project, Python provides the core logic behind the system, such as handling logins, processing orders, and linking the frontend to the database.

6.4.2 JavaScript (Frontend Development)
JavaScript is the main language used for building interactive web pages and is supported by all modern browsers without the need for extra setup. It makes it possible to create responsive and user-friendly interfaces that react quickly to user input. In this project, JavaScript is used to give both customers and staff a smooth experience, whether they are browsing products, placing orders, or managing stock.


6.4.3 MSSQL (Database)
MSSQL was chosen as the database because it is secure, reliable, and commonly used in real-world systems. It supports ACID transactions, which means customer orders and stock changes are stored correctly and consistently. It also has good security features and can handle growth if the business expands. Another advantage is that it connects well with Python through existing libraries, making development easier. Compared to lighter options like MSSQL is better for a web system where more than one user might be accessing it at the same time.
ACID
A = Atomicity → “All or nothing.”
If a customer places an order, either all parts of it are saved (order + order items), or none are saved if something fails.
C = Consistency → Data stays valid.
If an item has 10 in stock and someone buys 2, the stock must update to 8, not 9 or 11.
I = Isolation → One person’s order doesn’t mess with another person’s order, even if they happen at the same time
D = Durability → Once data is saved, it’s safe, even if the system crashes right after.
