7. System Design
7.1 UML Diagrams
7.1.1 Use Case Diagram
 
The Use Case Diagram shows how different users interact with the system and clearly defines what sits inside (and outside) the system boundary.
The main purpose of this diagram was to:
●	Define the system boundaries
●	Identify the core functional requirements
●	Clearly separate user roles (Customer, Staff, and Admin)
For this project, the actors were:
●	Customer – registers, logs in, browses the catalogue, places orders, and tracks their order status
●	Staff – updates inventory and manages incoming orders
●	Admin – manages users and generates reports
Creating this diagram early on helped me validate that every necessary interaction was accounted for before development started. It gave me clarity, reduced the risk of missing functionality, and ensured the system logic made sense before moving into implementation.
7.1.2 Sequence Diagram
 
The Sequence Diagram models the time-based interactions between different system components. Instead of focusing on structure, it shows how processes unfold step by step.
The purpose of this diagram was to:
●	Visualise frontend–backend communication
●	Model API calls clearly
●	Define the sequence of database interactions
In this project, the diagram illustrates the full request flow:
●	The Customer submits an order through the Java frontend
●	The backend (Python API) validates the request
●	The database stores the order
An inventory transaction is created
●	A confirmation response is returned to the user

Mapping this sequence helped me think through the system logically before integrating everything. It ensured that each layer, frontend, backend, and database communicated correctly and in the right order.
Rather than guessing how components should interact, this diagram supported intentional full-stack integration design and reduced integration errors during implementation.

7.1.3 Class Diagram
 
The Class Diagram models the static structure of the system. It represents how the core components are organised and how they relate to one another behind the scenes.
The purpose of this diagram was to:
●	Define the main entities and their relationships
●	Translate the database structure into an object-oriented format
●	Support the backend implementation in Python
In this project, the key classes identified were:
●	User
●	Product
●	Order
●	OrderItem
●	InventoryTransaction
Relationships such as one-to-many (e.g., one User to many Orders) were defined at this stage before implementing the database. This ensured the schema remained normalised, logically structured, and aligned with object-oriented principles.
Creating this diagram early allowed me to think through the architecture properly rather than just “coding and hoping.” It strengthened the backend design and reduced structural issues later in development.



7.2 Screen Flow 
7.2.1 Catalogue page (Customer)
 
The Catalogue Page serves as the main product discovery interface within the system. It is designed to present available products in a clear and structured way, making browsing straightforward and efficient.
The purpose of this page was to:
●	Display products in a grid format for easy comparison
●	Enable filtering and search functionality
●	Improve overall user experience
The design prioritises clarity, strong product visibility, and intuitive navigation. The grid layout allows users to quickly scan multiple products at once, while filtering and search features reduce friction in the browsing process.
Rather than overwhelming the user with information, the layout focuses on simplicity and usability, ensuring that users can find what they need quickly and move seamlessly toward placing an order.


7.2.2 Checkout page (Customer)
 
The Checkout Page functions as the final step in the purchasing process, where users confirm their order and complete the transaction.
The purpose of this page was to:
●	Capture delivery details accurately
●	Present a clear order summary for review
●	Simulate payment confirmation
The layout was intentionally structured to reduce user friction and minimise input errors. Delivery fields are clearly labelled, the order summary provides transparency before confirmation, and the payment simulation ensures the transaction flow feels realistic and complete.
Rather than overwhelming the user at the final stage, the design focuses on clarity, logical progression, and validation. This helps prevent mistakes, builds user confidence, and ensures a smooth transition from selection to confirmation.











7.2.3 Staff pages (Login, Dashboard)
  
  
  



The Staff Interface includes a secure login page and an operational dashboard designed to support day-to-day management tasks.
The login page ensures that only authorised staff members can access internal system functionality, maintaining data security and role-based access control.
Once authenticated, staff are directed to the dashboard, which provides a structured overview of operational data. Clear visual indicators such as IN STOCK and OUT OF STOCK statuses allow staff to immediately identify inventory issues without needing to dig through records.
The purpose of this interface is to:
●	Monitor incoming and processed orders
●	Adjust inventory levels when required
●	View sales summaries to track performance
The dashboard was designed for clarity and speed. Key information is surfaced prominently so staff can make quick, informed decisions. By reducing unnecessary navigation and highlighting critical data points, the interface supports operational efficiency and effective decision-making.
Rather than functioning as just an admin panel, this area of the system acts as the operational control centre - ensuring inventory accuracy, order flow consistency, and overall business visibility.



