8. Testing
This test strategy defines the structured approach used to validate that the Digital Order Booking System meets the functional, non-functional, security, and business requirements identified during the requirements gathering phase with the Mides Collection business owner.
 8.1 Test Objectives
Aligned to the stated project objectives, testing must confirm that:
•	Customers can browse products, place orders, and receive instant confirmations
•	Orders are automatically routed to staff and the wholesaler
•	Staff can log in securely, manage orders, and update inventory
•	Customer data is protected using SHA2_512 password hashing and role-based access
•	The database maintains ACID compliance, referential integrity, and accurate stock levels
•	The system performs reliably under normal and edge-case conditions
8.2 Test Scope
8.2.1 In Scope
•	All 7 functional MVP requirements (product browsing, order placement, confirmation, staff dashboard, inventory update, secure login, wholesaler notification)
•	All 5 non-functional requirements (usability, security, reliability, performance, scalability)
•	Full MidesInventory database — 12 tables, 8 stored procedures, 5 views, triggers, constraints
•	Three-tier integration: JavaScript frontend → Python API → MSSQL database
•	Security: SHA2_512 password hashing, session tokens, audit logging, RBAC
8.2.2 Out of Scope
•	Real payment gateway processing (simulated only, per project scope)
•	Advanced marketing or CRM tools (future development phase)
•	Third-party wholesaler API integration (notification only, not full integration)
8.2.3 Test Levels & Approach
The project follows a Hybrid Waterfall-Agile methodology, so testing is structured sequentially but with iterative verification within each phase.
8.3 Unit Testing
Tests individual functions and modules in isolation.
Component	Tool	What Is Tested
Python backend functions	pytest	Order processing logic, input validation, login handler
JavaScript UI components	Jest	Product search filter, cart total calculation, form validation
MSSQL stored procedures	MSSQL Studio	sp_UserLogin, sp_AddInwardTransaction, sp_AddOutwardTransaction 
Database constraints	T-SQL debugger	CHECK constraints, UNIQUE constraints, NOT NULL rules

8.4 Integration Testing
Tests communication across system layers: frontend ↔ Python API ↔ MSSQL.
Key Integration Flows to Test:
•	Customer Order Flow: JS checkout form → POST /api/orders → Python validates → MSSQL OutwardTransactions + Inventory updated
•	Staff Login Flow: JS login form → POST /api/login → sp_UserLogin → SHA2_512 hash verified → session token returned → UserSessions created
•	Purchase Order Workflow: Staff creates PO → sp_CreatePurchaseOrder → PurchaseOrders + PurchaseOrderDetails created → sp_ReceivePurchaseOrder → stock incremented
•	Inventory Update: Inward/outward transaction → trg_AuditInventory fires → AuditLog entry created
