9. Implementation 
The implementation of the Digital Order Booking System transformed earlier analysis and design decisions into a functional three-tier architecture consisting of a JavaScript presentation layer, a Python application layer, and a Microsoft SQL Server data layer. Structuring the system ensured clear separation between user interaction, business logic, and data management. This modularity reduced tight coupling and supports future scalability without requiring structural redesign.
All critical operations, including authentication, order processing, and inventory updates, were enforced at backend and database level rather than client-side. This decision strengthened system integrity by preventing manipulation through the interface. Order placement was implemented using transactional stored procedures to ensure atomicity. Stock deductions and order creation occur within a single ACID-compliant transaction, preventing partial failures from compromising data consistency.
Referential integrity was maintained through primary and foreign key constraints across entities such as Users, Orders, Products, and Inventory. The schema reflects Third Normal Form principles, reducing redundancy and improving consistency. Security controls included salted SHA2_512 password hashing, failed login tracking, account lockout mechanisms, session token generation, and expiry validation. Error handling was designed so detailed failures are logged internally while generic responses are returned to users, reducing the risk of information disclosure.
Performance optimisation included indexed keys, computed stock fields, and carefully scoped transactions to minimise locking duration. This makes the system appropriate for small-to-medium transaction volumes within the intended business context.
As a Level 5 student, translating theory into a fully functioning implementation presented challenges. Maintaining schema consistency while refining stored procedures required iterative testing and frequent refactoring. Balancing academic expectations with practical development constraints also required disciplined time management and independent problem-solving. There were moments where aligning database normalisation theory with real-world usability considerations felt complex, particularly when evolving requirements required structural adjustments. However, these challenges strengthened my understanding of applied database design beyond theoretical models.
While the system satisfies both functional and non-functional requirements identified earlier, it remains extensible. Future enhancements could include payment gateway integration, cloud deployment, or adoption of adaptive hashing algorithms to further strengthen enterprise-level security.
Overall, the implementation demonstrates applied database theory, secure coding practice, and structured system development aligned with BCS Level 5 expectations, while also reflecting the learning curve involved in progressing from academic concepts to production-style thinking.






10. Legal, Ethical, Social, and Professional (LESP) Issues
10.1 Legal
The system stores customer names, contact details, and order history, so data protection laws (such as GDPR in the UK/EU) is considered. Personal data will be stored securely in the database, with limited staff access. Passwords will be encrypted, and sensitive information will not be shared outside the business. Since no real payment system is implemented, financial regulations are not a priority, but still respect data confidentiality.
10.2 Ethical
Ethically, the system will be designed to serve customers fairly. For example, confirmations should be accurate, and order records should not be changed without reason. The interface should be clear, avoiding misleading information. Transparency in how customer data is used (only for order processing, not for marketing unless consent is given) is also an ethical concern.
10.3 Social
Socially, the system helps the business run more smoothly and improves customer experience by reducing delays and errors. However, some customers may not have regular internet access, so the business should still allow for alternative ordering methods. Accessibility features such as clear text, mobile compatibility, and simple navigation will ensure the system can be used by a wider audience.
10.4 Professional
As a future IT professional, I must follow the BCS Code of Conduct. This means being honest in reporting results, respecting confidentiality, and maintaining high standards of testing and documentation. Professional practice also involves considering system security from the beginning, not as an afterthought.













11. Evaluation 
The project focused on designing and implementing a secure, scalable, and user-friendly digital order booking system for a hair and accessories business, addressing order inaccuracies, inconsistent stock tracking, and limited operational visibility.
All primary objectives were achieved. A web-based ordering system allows customers to browse products, place orders, and receive confirmations using a Java frontend integrated with a Python backend and MSSQL database. Referential integrity constraints maintain transactional consistency. Inventory management was automated through structured inward and outward transaction procedures, with stock threshold alerts reducing manual oversight.
Secure role-based access control was implemented using salted SHA2-512 hashing, session tokens, expiry controls, and lockout protection. The security model is appropriate for small-scale deployment, though multi-factor authentication would strengthen resilience. Operational traceability was implemented through structured logging; however, graphical dashboards and KPI-based reporting were not developed, limiting analytical depth.
Testing covered unit, integration, user acceptance, and negative scenarios. All critical cases—including invalid logins, lockout enforcement, insufficient stock handling, duplicate account prevention, and purchase order processing—passed successfully. No critical defects remained at completion, although performance and stress testing were not conducted.
Key strengths include 3NF database normalisation, ACID-compliant transactions, audit logging, brute-force protection, and modular architecture. Limitations include no payment gateway integration, limited analytics capability, lack of replication, and no horizontal scaling. The system supports vertical optimisation and future cloud deployment. GDPR-aligned security practices were implemented, with scope for enhanced data governance controls.

12. Conclusion
This project successfully demonstrates applied systems analysis, relational database design, security implementation, and full-stack integration within a real-world commercial scenario.
The developed solution addresses previously identified operational inefficiencies, including manual order tracking, inconsistent stock updates, and fragmented communication workflows.
Technically, the system exceeds minimum Level 5 expectations through the implementation of:
•	ACID-compliant transactional procedures
•	Salted password hashing
•	Account lockout protection
•	Audit logging
•	Structured inventory lifecycle management
Although advanced analytics and payment gateway integration were outside scope, the system architecture supports future expansion.
Overall, this project reflects not only technical competence but structured analytical thinking, secure system design, and professional software engineering practice consistent with BCS Level 5 standards.

